DWELL

PURPOSE
Watch internal C state at explicit sampling points.

dwell is no longer a second stdin key/value checker. trip owns external stream
checking. dwell owns in-process state observation: register variables or reader
callbacks, attach libctc rules, and call ctc_dwell_tick() from the program.

EXAMPLE

#include <ctc.h>

ctc_dwell_ctx ctx;
volatile uint32_t queue_depth = 0;

ctc_dwell_init(&ctx);
ctc_dwell_add_rule(&ctx, "worker.queue.depth", CTC_GT, 1000.0,
                   CTC_ERROR, "queue.backpressure");
ctc_dwell_watch_u32(&ctx, "worker.queue.depth", &queue_depth);

queue_depth = 1201;
ctc_dwell_tick(&ctx);

ATLAS
atlas can generate the key constants used by dwell:

atlas header examples/rover/telemetry.atlas > telemetry_ids.h

CLI
The dwell executable is only a tiny demonstration harness for now:

./dwell --demo

Use trip for Unix pipelines:

program | trip -r rules.trip

